{"id":"1706.02308","submitter":"Krzysztof Nalewajko","authors":"Krzysztof Nalewajko, Maitrayee Gupta","title":"The sequence of Compton dominance in blazars based on data from WISE and\n  Fermi/LAT","comments":"9 pages, 5 figures, submitted to A&A","journal-ref":"A&A 606, A44 (2017)","doi":"10.1051/0004-6361/201731329","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE astro-ph.GA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The two-component broad-band spectral energy distributions of blazars were\nsuggested to form a sequence in which (1) the peak frequency of the low-energy\n(synchrotron) component nu_syn is anticorrelated with the synchrotron\nluminosity L_syn, and (2) the luminosity ratio of the high-energy (inverse\nCompton) to synchrotron components q = L_IC / L_syn (Compton dominance)\nincreases with L_syn from the BL Lac objects (BL Lacs) to the flat spectrum\nradio quasars (FSRQs). The Compton dominance parameter is an important probe of\nplasma magnetisation in the blazar zones within relativistic jets. We\ninvestigate a sample of blazars detected by WISE in the mid-infrared (MIR) band\nand by Fermi/LAT in the GeV gamma-ray band, with the focus on the distribution\nof luminosities and photon indices. Our findings are the following: (1) the MIR\nphoton index Gamma_W12 is a useful probe of the blazar sequence, with the\nexception of low-luminosity BL Lacs that are most likely contaminated by their\nhost galaxies (L_W1 ~ 10^44 erg/s and Gamma_W12 < 1); (2) Gamma_W12 is\ncorrelated with the gamma-ray photon index Gamma_1-100GeV, with the MIR\nluminosity L_W1, and with the Fermi/WISE Compton dominance q_FW = L_1GeV/L_W1;\n(3) a clean separation between FSRQs and BL Lacs can be seen in the parameter\nspace of Gamma_W12 and q_FW; (4) the observed distribution of MIR luminosity\nL_W1 vs. Compton dominance q_FW for the entire sample of blazars can be modeled\nas a sequence of lepto-magnetic jet powers in the range (log_10 P_eB) in\n[42:45] with the preference for sub-equipartition magnetic fields P_B/P_e in\n[0.05:1], assuming fixed bulk Lorentz factor Gamma_j = 15, fixed jet opening\nangle Gamma_j Theta_j = 0.3, fixed radiative efficiency of jet electrons\nepsilon_em = 50%, and that external radiation luminosity scales like L_ext\npropto (P_eB)^(1.6) (parameter degeneracies are discussed).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 7 Jun 2017 18:00:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-10-11"}
{"id":"1706.02309","submitter":"Bin Liu","authors":"Bin Liu, Dong Lai","title":"Spin-Orbit Misalignment of Merging Black-Hole Binaries with Tertiary\n  Companions","comments":"Published in ApJL","journal-ref":"The Astrophysical Journal Letters, 2017, Volume 846, L11","doi":"10.3847/2041-8213/aa8727","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the effect of external companion on the orbital and spin evolution\nof merging black-hole (BH) binaries. An sufficiently close by and inclined\ncompanion can excite Lidov-Kozai (LK) eccentricity oscillations in the binary,\nthereby shortening its merger time. During such LK-enhanced orbital decay, the\nspin axis of the BH generally exhibits chaotic evolution, leading to a wide\nrange ($0^\\circ$-$180^\\circ$) of final spin-orbit misalignment angle from an\ninitially aligned configuration. For systems that do not experience\neccentricity excitation, only modest ($\\lesssim 20^\\circ$) spin-orbit\nmisalignment can be produced, and we derive an analytic expression for the\nfinal misalignment using the principle of adiabatic invariance. The spin-orbit\nmisalignment directly impacts the gravitational waveform, and can be used to\nconstrain the formation scenarios of BH binaries and dynamical influences of\nexternal companions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 7 Jun 2017 18:00:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 3 Sep 2017 00:46:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-09-05"}
